There is an upcoming launch and we discover something is broken, 
the other team owns it. Walk me through the process of error discovery, 
identifying the right owner and fixing the issue before the big launch tomorrow.


Alert fires: CB open / high 5xx / timeouts / latency spike
Check dashboards: confirm real spike vs noise
Go to logs: find request_id / trace_id → see failing service
Isolate dependency: which backend is failing (DB / downstream service)
Identify owner: service name → service catalog / on-call (PagerDuty)
Escalate fast: page owning team + share logs + impact
Mitigate: rollback / feature flag off / fallback / traffic shift
Verify: error rate normal, CB closed, latency back




If we have to co-develop an app with help from partner team,
what are the things you'd do to ensure faster delivery (he was looking for answer from a tech perspective and not process perspective).



Clear API contracts (OpenAPI/Proto) before coding
Mock servers / stubs so both teams can develop in parallel
Backward-compatible APIs + versioning (avoid blocking each other)
Shared schemas/models (or strict schema governance)
Feature flags to merge early without breaking prod
Event-driven integration (Kafka/pub-sub) where possible to decouple services
Well-defined error codes + tracing (correlation IDs) for debugging fast
